Based on the search results, here's information about UXP Premiere Pro manifest.json entry points for panels and commands:

## UXP Manifest.json Entry Points for Premiere Pro

### Key Information

Each UXP plugin must have one manifest.json file that the host application uses to load and manage the plugin.(no content)In addition to core metadata such as the plugin's name, version, icons, and entry points, the manifest specifies permissions, compatibility details, and other definitions that shape how the plugin integrates with the host environment.(no content)Premiere supports manifest version "5".(no content)The type of entrypoint currently supports only Commands and Panels.(no content)The ID of the entrypoint must be unique within the plugin and is used to identify the code that implements the entrypoint.

### Example manifest.json with Command Entry Point

In your manifest.json file, register a new command-type entrypoint:

```json
{
  // ...
  "entrypoints": [
    {
      "type": "command",
      "id": "myCommand",
      "label": "My Command"
    }
  ]
}
```

This will add a new command entrypoint with the ID "myCommand" to your plugin. It will show up as My Command in the Premiere Pro user interface.

### Example with Both Panel and Command Entry Points

Here's a more complete example structure:

```json
{
  "manifestVersion": 5,
  "id": "yourPluginId",
  "name": "My UXP Plugin",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "main": "index.html",
  "host": {
    "app": "premierepro",
    "minVersion": "25.0.0"
  },
  "entrypoints": [
    {
      "type": "command",
      "id": "myCommand",
      "label": { "default": "My Command" }
    },
    {
      "type": "panel",
      "id": "myPanel",
      "label": { "default": "My Panel" }
    }
  ]
}
```

### JavaScript Handler Setup

There are two ways to add a command entrypoint to your plugin's code. In your JavaScript code (for example, in your index.js), add the following code:

```javascript
const { entrypoints } = require("uxp");
entrypoints.setup({
  commands: {
    myCommand: myCommandHandler
  }
});
```

Note that myCommand is the ID of the command entrypoint we registered in the manifest.(no content)Command entrypoints are the most common type of entrypoint. They allow you to add commands to the Premiere Pro user interface. When the user runs a command, your plugin can perform a variety of actions, such as opening a dialog and changing the document.


