Based on the search results, here's what I found about the UXP manifest v5 schema, including information about `requiredPermissions`, `host`, `app`, and `minVersion`:

## UXP Manifest v5 Overview

Manifest v5 gives developers access to a new plugin permissions model and WebViews in modal dialogs. Using the full manifest v5 feature set requires PS 23.3.0 or higher.

### Basic Manifest Structure

Each UXP plugin has one manifest.json file that describes the plugin. It contains metadata such as the plugin's name, version, icons, and entry points. The manifest file also contains the permissions that the plugin requires. Most importantly, it contains your plugin ID which is used to identify your plugin.

### Host Configuration

The "host" is now an array of objects in Manifest v5, which supports multi-host UXP plugins (at the moment Photoshop and Adobe XD).(no content)The "minVersion" must be at least "23.3.0" for Photoshop.

Example host configuration:
```json
"host": [
  {
    "app": "PS",
    "minVersion": "23.3.0",
    "data": {
      "apiVersion": 2
    }
  }
]
```

There's a new "data" property, where you can specify the "apiVersion": set it to 2.

### Required Permissions

To ensure that plugins are secure, UXP requires that plugins declare the permissions they need to function. Make sure you configure the most accurate permission for your use case because in the future we will ask users to provide their consent based on it.(no content)Users will be asked for their consent when your plugin attempts to use openExternal, openPath, and sp-link/anchor tags. For everything else, consent is given at install time.

Example `requiredPermissions` structure:
```json
"requiredPermissions": {
  "launchProcess": {
    "schemes": ["https", "mailto", "file"],
    "extensions": [".pdf"]
  },
  "network": {
    "domains": ["https://example.com"]
  },
  "allowCodeGenerationFromStrings": true,
  "localFileSystem": "plugin",
  "clipboard": "read"
}
```

### Network Permissions

The network permission specifies the domains that the plugin can access in network requests. You can also allow access to all domains by setting domains to "all".(no content)requiredPermissions needs domains under network. Sites works under permissions but UXP wants requiredPermissions and not permissions. The network permissions work as long as you have a domain name and not an IP address.

### Complete Example Manifest

```json
{
  "manifestVersion": 5,
  "id": "YOUR_ID_HERE",
  "name": "Name of your plugin",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "main": "index.html",
  "host": {
    "app": "PS",
    "minVersion": "23.3.0"
  },
  "entrypoints": [
    {
      "type": "command",
      "id": "commandFn",
      "label": { "default": "Show A Dialog" }
    },
    {
      "type": "panel",
      "id": "panelName",
      "label": { "default": "Panel Name" }
    }
  ],
  "icons": [
    {
      "width": 24,
      "height": 24,
      "path": "icons/icon.png",
      "scale": [1, 2]
    }
  ],
  "requiredPermissions": {
    "network": {
      "domains": "all"
    }
  }
}
```

The manifestVersion property determines which features the plugin may support and requires specific Photoshop versions in order to run. Version 5 is the latest available and enables most recent features introduced by UXP 6.0 and requires at least Photoshop 23.3.0.


